234
00:35:28,543 --> 00:35:30,837
<i>and he knows when she's serious.</i>

235
00:35:39,303 --> 00:35:42,223
<i>Adult seals make a much better meal.</i>

236
00:35:54,026 --> 00:35:57,238
<i>Her cub carefully treads in her footsteps,</i>

237
00:35:59,574 --> 00:36:02,285
<i>and takes care not to break her outline.</i>

238
00:36:06,622 --> 00:36:08,791
<i>Neither must put a foot wrong.</i>

239
00:36:15,756 --> 00:36:18,176
<i>They must move as one.</i>

240
00:36:44,577 --> 00:36:47,538
<i>Most seal hunts end in failure.</i>

241
00:36:55,171 --> 00:36:57,215
<i>The bears must keep searching.</i>

242
00:37:01,344 --> 00:37:03,554
<i>Her cub wanders off,</i>

243
00:37:06,182 --> 00:37:07,850
<i>and gets another chance.</i>

244
00:37:18,611 --> 00:37:21,447
<i>A seal pup alone on the ice.</i>

245
00:37:26,327 --> 00:37:29,330
[seal pup whimpering]

246
00:37:32,166 --> 00:37:36,754
<i>Now it's not stealth
that is needed, but confidence.</i>

247
00:37:41,842 --> 00:37:43,886
<i>There's nothing the mother can do,</i>

248
00:37:46,472 --> 00:37:50,559
<i>except hope that the pup makes it
back to her hole in time.</i>

249
00:37:51,811 --> 00:37:52,811
[whimpers]

250
00:37:58,150 --> 00:38:00,987
<i>The inexperienced young hunter
hesitates.</i>

251
00:38:11,330 --> 00:38:12,873
<i>Its mother knows better.</i>

252
00:38:36,939 --> 00:38:38,941
<i>Safe under the ice.</i>

253
00:38:44,947 --> 00:38:50,536
<i>Polar bears are adaptable predators,
but they rely on sea ice.</i>

254
00:38:52,455 --> 00:38:56,125
<i>If that disappears, so will the bears.</i>

255
00:39:10,222 --> 00:39:13,768
<i>Summer at the ice edge
in the Canadian Arctic,</i>

256
00:39:14,352 --> 00:39:18,189
<i>and the annual retreat of sea ice
is well underway.</i>

257
00:39:27,782 --> 00:39:30,701
<i>As it melts, nomads arrive.</i>

258
00:39:50,304 --> 00:39:54,433
<i>Narwhal, the origin of the unicorn legend.</i>

259
00:39:55,267 --> 00:40:01,190
<i>Their three-meter tusk is, in fact,
no more than an overgrown canine tooth,</i>

260
00:40:02,149 --> 00:40:06,362
<i>but its exact function,
like so much about narwhals,</i>

261
00:40:06,695 --> 00:40:08,948
<i>is still, in part, a mystery.</i>

262
00:40:14,662 --> 00:40:18,374
<i>Each summer,Â narwhals travel
to the same part of the Arctic,</i>

263
00:40:18,749 --> 00:40:23,129
<i>and patiently wait at the ice edge
for a crack to open up.</i>

264
00:40:26,173 --> 00:40:30,136
<i>A lead in the ice,
wide enough for them to swim along.</i>

265
00:40:43,441 --> 00:40:45,568
<i>Eventually, a crack appears.</i>

266
00:40:47,903 --> 00:40:50,906
<i>Their passage to sheltered, shallow bays.</i>

267
00:41:12,261 --> 00:41:16,849
<i>Narwhals are extremely timid
and rarely filmed underwater.</i>

268
00:41:44,835 --> 00:41:49,340
<i>These ice whalesÂ eagerly travel
down the leads as soon as they open</i>

269
00:41:49,548 --> 00:41:52,718
<i>because they're safer from predators
protected by the ice.</i>

270
00:42:01,560 --> 00:42:05,439
<i>The leads may also give them access
to new feeding grounds.</i>

271
00:42:18,786 --> 00:42:20,579
<i>Sea ice is not just crucial</i>

272
00:42:20,663 --> 00:42:23,707
<i>to the lives of those creatures
that live around the poles.</i>

273
00:42:25,709 --> 00:42:30,381
<i>It plays a vital role in determining
the climate of the whole planet.</i>

274
00:42:33,551 --> 00:42:36,136
<i>A white surface keeps the earth cool</i>

275
00:42:36,387 --> 00:42:40,307
<i>by reflecting most of the sun's energy
back into space.</i>

276
00:42:50,693 --> 00:42:52,903
<i>A dark surface does the opposite,</i>

277
00:42:53,904 --> 00:42:56,824
<i>absorbing over 90 percent
of the sun's energy</i>

278
00:42:57,199 --> 00:42:58,826
<i>and so warming the earth.</i>

279
00:43:03,372 --> 00:43:04,707
<i>As the sea ice shrinks,</i>

280
00:43:04,999 --> 00:43:09,795
<i>we're starting to lose one of our planet's
protective white shields.</i>

281
00:43:13,966 --> 00:43:15,384
<i>For thousands of years,</i>

282
00:43:15,593 --> 00:43:19,430
<i>there's been a balance
in the advance and retreat of the sea ice,</i>

283
00:43:20,180 --> 00:43:21,807
<i>but that is no longer the case.</i>

284
00:43:22,558 --> 00:43:24,685
<i>Today, during the summer months,</i>

285
00:43:24,935 --> 00:43:30,065
<i>there is 40 percent less sea ice cover
than there was in 1980.</i>

286
00:43:39,533 --> 00:43:44,288
<i>The Arctic is warming twice as fast
as anywhere else on our planet.</i>

287
00:43:45,247 --> 00:43:50,210
<i>By 2040, the ocean here
will be largely free of ice</i>

288
00:43:50,419 --> 00:43:51,754
<i>during the summer months.</i>

289
00:44:09,229 --> 00:44:14,193
<i>This loss of iceÂ will inevitably
have devastating consequences</i>

290
00:44:14,526 --> 00:44:16,737
<i>for all those that still depend on it.</i>

291
00:44:21,158 --> 00:44:23,369
[birds cawing]

292
00:44:30,167 --> 00:44:33,504
<i>The far northeastern coast
of Russia.</i>

293
